                <h2>Languages of Taiwan: The Breath of the Land</h2>
                <h3>1. Taiwanese Mandarin: Unique Accents</h3>
                <p>This is the primary official and common language in Taiwan. Used in government, education, and business, Taiwanese Mandarin has developed its own unique accent and vocabulary, often described as gentler than in other regions.</p>
                
                <h4>Distinctive Habits:</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Slurred Phonetics:</strong> Words are often slurred. For example, "motorcycle" (m√≥-tu≈ç-chƒì) often evolves into "m√≥-o-chƒì".</li>
                    <li><strong>Merging of Sounds:</strong> Speakers often do not distinguish between "en" and "eng", or "an" and "ang".</li>
                    <li><strong>Local Pronunciations:</strong> A notable quirk is pronouncing "very cold" (hƒõn lƒõng) as "hƒõn nƒõng".</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
